{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.05,0.73,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9401"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11193"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22255"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute confusion and difficulty communicating. Her family reports that she is speaking fluently but not making sense, and does not seem to understand what they are saying to her. She has a history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation, for which she takes amlodipine and warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her speech is fluent but contains nonsensical words and phrases. She is unable to follow simple commands or repeat words. The remainder of her neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of aphasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transcortical motor aphasia","Transcortical sensory aphasia","Conduction aphasia","Wernicke\u0027s aphasia","Broca\u0027s aphasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u0027s aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E: fluent but nonsensical speech (often called \u0027word salad\u0027), poor comprehension, and inability to repeat. This pattern occurs due to damage to the posterior superior temporal gyrus, typically from stroke in the territory of the posterior division of the middle cerebral artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroca\u0027s aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by non-fluent, effortful speech with preserved comprehension. Patients often speak in short phrases and have difficulty with grammar, though their speech content is appropriate. This results from damage to the inferior frontal gyrus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduction aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E features fluent speech with preserved comprehension but poor repetition. This occurs due to damage to the arcuate fasciculus, disconnecting Wernicke\u0027s and Broca\u0027s areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscortical motor aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E presents with non-fluent speech but preserved comprehension and repetition. It results from lesions in the frontal lobe anterior or superior to Broca\u0027s area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscortical sensory aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is similar to Wernicke\u0027s aphasia but with preserved repetition. It occurs with lesions that isolate Wernicke\u0027s area from other language areas while preserving the connection to Broca\u0027s area.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wernicke\u0027s aphasia is characterised by fluent speech with poor comprehension and repetition.","The location of language areas in the brain determines the pattern of aphasia symptoms.","Assessment of fluency, comprehension, and repetition helps localise the lesion in aphasia."],"references":["Acharya AB, Wroten M. Wernicke Aphasia. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722980.","Sheppard SM, Sebastian R. Diagnosing and managing post-stroke aphasia. Expert Rev Neurother. 2021 Feb;21(2):221-234. doi: 10.1080/14737175.2020.1855976. Epub 2020 Dec 10. PMID: 33231117; PMCID: PMC7880889","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Tan, Y., Zhang, LM., Liang, Xl. et al. A literature review and meta-analysis of the optimal factors study of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation in post-infarction aphasia. Eur J Med Res 29, 18 (2024). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40001-023-01525-5","Tippett DC, Niparko JK, Hillis AE. Aphasia: Current Concepts in Theory and Practice. J Neurol Transl Neurosci. 2014 Jan;2(1):1042. PMID: 24904925; PMCID: PMC4041294"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T16:59:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T17:00:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items